messages.text: At 6 PM that night, Wren sends Ember another picture of herself.
Ember laughs at the goofy look on the face of the blonde woman with brown eyes and pale skin. She‚Äôs standing in a kitchen.
Just got home! Phew. ER was busy this afternoon.
Ember types a response quickly before she loses courage.
You have a very kissable mouth.
So do you‚Ä¶and killer eyes. I can‚Äôt wait to see you.
Maybe someday‚Ä¶
Someday is too far away. How about a picture to pass the time?
Another one?
It‚Äôs only fair. I sent you a bonus pic.
Ember snaps a photo, cropping out the hospital bed and heart monitor. Then she sends it.
So pretty‚Ä¶
It looks like you‚Äôre in the same place you took the last photo.
I don‚Äôt get out much.
Wait a minute!
Are you an astronaut?!
Ember laughs.
No! Nothing that exciting.
So I‚Äôm not getting any closer?
You‚Äôre almost a galaxy away üë©‚ÄçüöÄ üòâ
Lol. I really like talking to you.
I like it too. You have no idea‚Ä¶
What?
You have no idea how much you break up the monotony of my day.
More vague hints, huh?
Sorry.
It‚Äôs ok. It‚Äôs just‚Ä¶I‚Äôm curious if we have chemistry in person.
Waiting to find out is killing me.
I‚Äôm sure girls are falling all over themselves for you.
Ha. Like the girl from the bar?
Not exactly.
How about a good hint? Please?
Before Ember can think of something, a new text comes in from Wren.
What do you do for work?
That question should be easy enough.
I can‚Äôt work right now.
Okay. Well, just so you know‚Ä¶
I‚Äôm not going to stop bothering you until you agree to meet üòõ
Stalker üòâ
Yup.
You know if a guy said that, any sane person would block him.
Gotta love double standards.
So a hint?
Okay. Well‚Ä¶
She looks around the room.
Where I live is both quiet and noisy, often at the same time. It smells like disinfectant.
My best friend is short and stout, always by my side, and keeps me alive.
There‚Äôs another long pause and Ember wonders if she scared Wren away.
Her nephrologist walks into the room.
Gotta go. Be back tomorrow.
Maybe.
In the middle of the night, Ember wakes up sweating.
She‚Äôs in severe pain and is feeling nauseas. She hits the CALL button next to the bed‚Äî
And blacks out just as the night nurse rushes in.
A few hours later, Ember opens her eyes. There are people all around her.
Off in a corner, she spots someone who reminds her of the photo Wren sent of herself.
Figuring she‚Äôs delirious, Ember falls back asleep.
Later in the morning, Ember is fully awake when a nurse walks into her room.
She‚Äôs sitting up in bed with an IV pumping antibiotics into her body to clear up another kidney infection.
You‚Äôve moved up the transplant list.
I guess there‚Äôs something to be said for almost dying.
We don‚Äôt plan on losing you, sweetie.
Ember smiles slightly.
I like that attitude. Did someone call my mom?
I‚Äôm not sure. Want me to get your phone?
Ember nods. The nurse takes her phone off the charger on the floor and hands it to Ember.
Ember dials her mom‚Äôs number then waits for her to pick-up.
Good morning, honey! Is it morning there? I‚Äôve lost track of the time zones.
Yes, it‚Äôs morning. How‚Äôs work?
Tiring. I love China but the city is getting overwhelming. Only a week left and then I‚Äôll be home.
Ember closes her eyes, pushing back her tears.
She wishes her mom were here right now. Her dad left when she was a baby‚Ä¶
And it‚Äôs been her and her mom ever since.
She‚Äôs Ember‚Äôs best friend.
Mom? I have to tell you something.
When Ember‚Äôs mom speaks, her voice sounds alarmed.
What‚Äôs wrong? Is everything okay?
Yes. It‚Äôs fine. Just a rough night.
There‚Äôs something you‚Äôre not telling me.
I was moved up the transplant list.
I would say that‚Äôs good but I‚Äôm sure there‚Äôs a reason that happened.
Like I said, rough night.
Want me to come there now?
I can book a flight for this afternoon.
No, no. There‚Äôs no point.
I‚Äôm stable now, so I‚Äôll just be sitting here waiting‚Ä¶
Whether you‚Äôre here or there.
Reluctantly, Ember‚Äôs mom answers.
Okay, but you keep me updated, okay?
I can always finish up these last meetings on Skype if I have to.
Okay.
Promise me you‚Äôll tell me if anything changes.
I promise.
Ember spots a vase of flowers on the table in her room.
They weren‚Äôt there before ‚Äî right?
Um. I gotta go.
Okay, honey. I love you.
Love you too.
Ember hangs up and turns to the nurse.
Where did those come from?
A woman dropped them off. She didn‚Äôt say her name.
She was in scrubs but I didn‚Äôt recognize her.
The nurse shrugs.
Definitely not from the nephrology department.
Suddenly, Ember has a flashback from the recovery room.
Didn‚Äôt she see someone who looked like Wren when she was feverish?
Can you hand me the card?
Sure thing, sweetie.
Ember reads the message on the card‚Ä¶
You‚Äôre even more gorgeous in person. Get well soon.
Panicked, Ember fumbles for her phone and checks her messages.
There‚Äôs only one text and it‚Äôs from two days ago.
I won‚Äôt bug you, but please let me know when you‚Äôre feeling okay.
Ember flips to her text message chain with Wren. With shaking hands, she begins typing.
Were you here?
Like, in my room when I was sick?
She stares at the phone ‚Äî half shocked, half mortified.
Yes.
How did you find me?
I figured it out. The disinfectant smell. The picture of the wallpaper‚Ä¶
And I‚Ä¶I searched the hospital database for you, since your name isn‚Äôt too common. Was that weird of me?
Ember‚Äôs heart races ‚Äî but then she thinks of Wren‚Äôs beautiful face‚Ä¶
And everything slows.
Actually, no. It‚Äôs more‚Ä¶sweet. Because it‚Äôs you.
Thank God! And don‚Äôt worry. I didn‚Äôt watch you sleep or anything. I just dropped the flowers off.
Are you‚Ä¶well enough to have visitors yet?
Do you know I went into kidney failure?
That I‚Äôm waiting for a transplant?
Um, you coded on a nephrology floor‚Äî
I put two and two together. I am a nurse üòâ
Ember swallows. Her hands shake as she types back.
I could die.
There‚Äôs a long pause.
Understood.
And‚Ä¶
You still want to meet me?
